Welcome back to Dry Powder. I=E2=80=99m Bill Cohan.

=C2=A0

Our friend Mike Mayo, the outspoken Wall Street analyst at Wells Fargo Secu=
rities, recently sounded the alarm about a new phenomenon in the world of c=
ommercial and investment banking: boards gifting their top executives so-ca=
lled =E2=80=9Cdouble bonuses=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94tens of millions of dollars o=
n top of their already remarkably healthy annual compensation packages. His=
 rant raises a worthy question: Should
shareholders celebrate the likes of Jamie Dimon and David Solomon receiving=
 additional tens of millions just for sticking around the building? More on=
 that, below the fold.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But first=E2=80=A6

* Elon
& Sam=E2=80=99s OpenAI pissing contest: I can=E2=80=99t begin to parse the =
madness animating Elon Musk=E2=80=99s latest flight of fancy: his unsolicit=
ed $97.4 billion offer for the nonprofit side of OpenAI. The idea, apparent=
ly, is that the nearly $100 billion investment would be used =E2=80=9Cirrev=
ocably=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9Ccharitable purposes,=E2=80=9D according to Mus=
k=E2=80=99s attorney, Marc Toberoff, in a statement/open letter/press relea=
se. =E2=80=9CIf Sam
Altman and the present OpenAI, Inc. Board of Directors are intent on becomi=
ng a fully for-profit corporation,=E2=80=9D wrote Toberoff, =E2=80=9Cit is =
vital that the charity be fairly compensated for what its leadership is tak=
ing away from it: control over the most transformative technology of our ti=
me.=E2=80=9D

Of course, this has less to do with Musk=E2=80=99s philanthropic spirit tha=
n his ongoing beef with Altman. The two men started OpenAI as a nonprofit, =
only for Sam to turn part of the company into
a for-profit enterprise that is now on the verge of raising ( https://puck.=
news/masayoshi-sons-legendary-career-as-told-by-his-biographer/?utm_campaig=
n=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustome=
r.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) some $40 billion in new capital from t=
he likes of SoftBank=E2=80=99s Masayoshi Son, at a valuation of around $350=
 billion. In short, they=E2=80=99re pissing at each other=E2=80=94Sam has r=
esponded with considerable snark both on X and Bloomberg TV=E2=80=94but I=
=E2=80=99m not sure that Elon=E2=80=99s offer has
much chance of success, given that OpenAI is a private entity and can do wh=
at it wants. Can=E2=80=99t Sam and his board just refuse to engage with Elo=
n and his investors and call it a day?=C2=A0

This is a million miles away from what Elon did with Twitter, which was a p=
ublic company, with shareholders who wanted the $44 billion in cash (at $54=
=2E20 per share) that Elon promised t=
hem before trying to renege. If I=E2=80=
=99m Sam and his board, I=E2=80=99m sending Elon et al. on their merry way=
=E2=80=94as long as
Microsoft, which owns 49 percent of OpenAI=E2=80=99s equity, and other boar=
d members and investors like Larry Summers and Josh Kushner, are similarly =
inclined. Note that Toberoff=E2=80=99s letter was not even sent to Sam, or =
to the nonprofit=E2=80=99s board, but rather to state officials in Californ=
ia and Delaware.=C2=A0

What I=E2=80=99ve found particularly amusing, though, has been Sam=E2=80=99=
s response. First, in an interview on Bloomberg TV, he emphasized that, of =
course,
OpenAI, and the OpenAI =E2=80=9Cmission,=E2=80=9D are not for sale. He thin=
ks Elon is just trying to =E2=80=9Cslow us down,=E2=80=9D because =E2=80=9C=
he=E2=80=99s raised a lot of money for xAI, and they=E2=80=99re trying to c=
ompete with us from a technological perspective, [and] getting the product =
into the market. I wish he would just compete by building a better product,=
 but I think there=E2=80=99s been a lot of tactics=E2=80=94many, many lawsu=
its, all sorts of other crazy stuff. Now this.=E2=80=9D Sam also said he =
=E2=80=9Cfeels=E2=80=9D for Elon because his =E2=80=9Cwhole life is from a
position of insecurity. =E2=80=A6 I don=E2=80=99t think he=E2=80=99s like, =
a happy person.=E2=80=9D Okay, then.

But what I=E2=80=99ve found most amusing has been Sam=E2=80=99s response to=
 the $97.4 billion offer itself. On X, of all places, he said =E2=80=9Cno t=
hank you=E2=80=9D to the bid, and added that =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=9D will =E2=
=80=9Cbuy twitter for $9.74 billion if you want.=E2=80=9D Musk=E2=80=99s re=
ply: =E2=80=9CSwindler.=E2=80=9D

I=E2=80=99m not sure if Sam was just offering to buy X for 10 percent of wh=
at Elon was offering for OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonprofit unit, or whether this w=
as an actual
reflection of what he thinks X is worth these days, or whether he=E2=80=99s=
 just goofing around with Elon about the most senior portion of the X debt,=
 which also amounts to around $9 billion. But interestingly, Sam=E2=80=99s =
approximate valuation would confirm what I have been saying all along=E2=80=
=94that the $31 billion of equity that Elon and his friends invested in Twi=
tter is long gone, and the only remaining question is the value of X=E2=80=
=99s $13 billion in debt. Under the Sam Altman construct, the debt is worth=
 75
cents on the dollar, or 9.74/13, which is a far cry from the 97 cents on th=
e dollar that some new investors reportedly paid for the senior tranche of =
the X debt last week. But I suspect Sam=E2=80=99s just having fun. Anyway, =
I=E2=80=99ll have more on that for Sunday.

And now, a word on the latest fad in investment banking=E2=80=A6

