The latest boardroom trend among the top banks is the phenomenon of =E2=80=
=9Cdouble
bonuses=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94paying ur-top executives not only for their perfor=
mance, but also to stick around without screwing the pooch.

William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%282%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Suddenly, it seems, so-called =E2=80=9Cdouble bonuses=E2=80=9D for C-suite =
executives on Wall Street are
all the rage, and Mike Mayo, the outspoken Wall Street research analyst at =
Wells Fargo Securities, has had enough. Indeed, with proxy and annual meeti=
ng season fast approaching, Mayo is calling out the boards of Goldman Sachs=
, as well as a trio of large commercial banks=E2=80=94KeyCorp, Truist Finan=
cial, and U.S. Bancorp=E2=80=94for gifting their top executives generous re=
tention-style bonuses that basically don=E2=80=99t require them to hit any =
meaningful performance metrics along the way. He hopes
investors will share his concerns, and make a stink about the bonuses, too.

=C2=A0

The enthusiasm for these kinds of compensation tactics seems to have starte=
d in July 2021, when the board of JPMorgan Chase awarded its fearless leade=
r, Jamie Dimon, a =E2=80=9Csurprise=E2=80=9D $50 million bonus=E2=80=94on t=
op of his annual compensation package of around $35 million that year=E2=80=
=94if he simply agreed to stick around for
another five years, something he obviously was planning to do anyway. (Heck=
, at this rate, he might still be the bank=E2=80=99s C.E.O. in 105 years.) =
In any event, since there was never any doubt he would be the C.E.O. until =
2026, it was easy money for Jamie, not that he needed it. At last count, hi=
s net worth was around $2.6 billion, derived principally from his shares in=
 JPMorgan Chase and the compensation he has received as its C.E.O. for the =
past 20 years. Well deserved, by the way=E2=80=A6 Under Jamie=E2=80=99s
leadership, JPMorgan Chase has become a money machine, generating annual ne=
t income in excess of $50 billion. The company is now worth more than $750 =
billion.

=C2=A0

Not to be outdone, in October 2021, Goldman Sachs awarded David Solomon, it=
s chairman and C.E.O., and John Waldron, its president, supposedly one-time=
 retention awards of restricted stock. The bonuses totaled roughly
$30 million for Solomon, on top of his 2021 compensation of around $35 mill=
ion, and roughly $20 million for Waldron. The idea was to ensure =E2=80=9Cc=
ontinuity=E2=80=9D of =E2=80=9Cleadership=E2=80=9D for the subsequent five =
years, and to keep the two men atop the firm amid the =E2=80=9Crapidly incr=
easing war for talent in the current environment.=E2=80=9D The awards were =
not only time-based; Solomon and Waldron also had to achieve performance me=
trics that were designed to =E2=80=9Calign compensation with rigorous perfo=
rmance thresholds that
drive long-term shareholder value creation,=E2=80=9D according to the Secur=
ities and Exchange Commission filings at the time.

=C2=A0

Well, it turns out Goldman may have been just kidding about the whole =E2=
=80=9Cone-time=E2=80=9D thing. In January, Goldman announced that Solomon a=
nd Waldron had been granted a fresh stock award of $80 million each. (That=
=E2=80=99s on top Solomon=E2=80=99s $39 million pay package last year.) And=
 this time, there were no
performance metrics attached. The two men simply have to stay in their jobs=
 for the next five years and not do anything dumb that could get them fired=
 for cause or participate in =E2=80=9Cmaterially improper risk analysis or =
failing to sufficiently raise concerns about risks,=E2=80=9D whatever that =
means.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Basically, the Goldman board wants to keep Solomon and Waldron around=E2=80=
=94Waldron had a recent, brief dalliance with
Apollo=E2=80=94to solidify the bank=E2=80=99s leadership for the next decad=
e or so. In the S.E.C. filing, Goldman stated it awarded the bonuses in ord=
er =E2=80=9Cto sustain the strong momentum [Solomon and Waldron] have demon=
strated in executing on our firmwide strategic priorities, [to] help ensure=
 stability and continuity in our senior leadership over the next five years=
 and [to] maintain a strong succession plan for the future of the firm.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Mayo, for his part, criticizes the Goldman board for being pushovers and is=
 urging Goldman shareholders to vote no on the nonbinding =E2=80=9Csay on p=
ay=E2=80=9D provision at the annual meeting in April. He=E2=80=99s also urg=
ing them to vote Kimberley Harris, the head of the Goldman board=E2=80=99s =
compensation committee, off the island=E2=80=94or at least to refuse to ren=
ominate her in that pivotal role. (Harris, a graduate of Yale Law School an=
d a former partner at Davis Polk, is the general
counsel of NBCUniversal and an executive vice president of Comcast.) =E2=80=
=9CWe disagree that this extra payment is in the interest of shareholders,=
=E2=80=9D Mayo wrote in his report.

=C2=A0

Mayo considers these large awards to be unnecessarily duplicative. =E2=80=
=9CWe have mixed feelings on C.E.O. and C.O.O. $80M retention bonus that is=
 separate and in addition to annual pay, which was up [25 percent] to $39M =
for the C.E.O in 2024,=E2=80=9D Mayo wrote. =E2=80=9CWe
view this as a =E2=80=98double bonus=E2=80=99 since this is in addition to =
the 2024 annual pay. Moreover, the reasons given for the $80M payment seem =
to overlap with those used to justify the higher 2024 pay (retention, strat=
egic momentum, succession, strategy, and performance).=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

Solomon=E2=80=99s
Succession
-----------

Mayo isn=E2=80=99t buying the argument that the new bonuses are rewards, of=
 sorts, for Goldman
mapping out its executive succession process, with Waldron designated to su=
cceed Solomon at some point. =E2=80=9CSuccession is a basic job of the C.E.=
O. and not one that should warrant a special bonus,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=
=80=9CIn our view, if David Solomon were to leave, we think that John Waldr=
on could fill in. While we recognize that it might take extra to keep John =
Waldron (though unvested stock is a motivator for him to say), there are ot=
hers who could replace him, too.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Mayo also suggested that Waldron could get paid more than Solomon=E2=80=94j=
ust as Tom Montag, a former top executive at Bank of America who is now on =
the Goldman board, was paid more than Brian Moynihan, the C.E.O. of Bank of=
 America, a few years ago. He additionally worried, considering the =E2=80=
=9Coverall comp ratio=E2=80=9D was down for the firm, that giving Solomon a=
nd Waldron these $80 million awards
could be =E2=80=9Calienating=E2=80=9D for Goldman executives who did not re=
ceive similar incentives.

=C2=A0

Mayo does acknowledge that Solomon and Waldron have done a =E2=80=9Cgood=E2=
=80=9D job of running Goldman Sachs, but not, he says, a =E2=80=9Cperfect=
=E2=80=9D job. (In fairness, Goldman=E2=80=99s stock is up 172 percent in t=
he past five years, more than that of its two main rivals, JPMorgan Chase a=
nd Morgan Stanley.) He noted that Goldman has shown =E2=80=9Cgood=E2=80=9D =
growth
in revenue, earnings, and book value, and is =E2=80=9Cbetter positioned=E2=
=80=9D now in its two main business lines, investment banking and wealth an=
d asset management.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

He was less enamored of the lackluster returns on equity, which the firm ha=
s been focused on improving. =E2=80=9CStrategically, they oversaw a costly =
and failed effort in consumer banking and what we see as a failed GreenSky =
acquisition,=E2=80=9D Mayo wrote,
referring to Goldman=E2=80=99s purchase and subsequent offloading of its co=
nsumer lending operations=E2=80=94Marcus, the Apple Card, etcetera. =E2=80=
=9CThe Apple Card portfolio remains and, if sold, may involve a loss.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

By the way, Mayo has a price target on Goldman=E2=80=99s stock of $680 per =
share, up about 5.3 percent from where it=E2=80=99s currently trading. I do=
n=E2=80=99t think Mayo is necessarily against Solomon and Waldron
getting these awards, but is simply annoyed at the relatively low lift invo=
lved. Five years may seem like a long time in our crazy world, but for exec=
utives to get this much compensation without having to achieve certain perf=
ormance metrics along the way=E2=80=94a return-on-equity target, a higher s=
tock price, anything, really, that is more substantial than just staying al=
ive and not doing something egregious=E2=80=94well, that seems a bit crazy =
too. A fair point, although I=E2=80=99m skeptical that enough
Goldman shareholders will flock to Mayo=E2=80=99s cause at the annual meeti=
ng.

=C2=A0

Goldman, for its part, said in a statement, =E2=80=9CThe firm has delivered=
 strong performance and the competition for our top talent has been especia=
lly fierce, including from asset managers and other non-banks.=E2=80=9D And=
 so the Goldman board of directors =E2=80=9Cwas determined to keep this tea=
m in place=E2=80=94both to maintain our momentum and to have a very strong =
succession
plan.=E2=80=9D The =E2=80=9Cvalue of a restricted stock award,=E2=80=9D the=
 bank spokesperson added, =E2=80=9Cis tied directly to the performance of t=
he company.=E2=80=9D

