9999999997px;"><strong>Solomon=E2=80=99s
Succession</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Mayo isn=E2=80=99t buying the argument that the new bonuses are rewards=
, of sorts, for Goldman
mapping out its executive succession process, with Waldron designated to su=
cceed Solomon at some point. =E2=80=9CSuccession is a basic job of the C.E.=
O. and not one that should warrant a special bonus,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=
=80=9CIn our view, if David Solomon were to leave, we think that John Waldr=
on could fill in. While we recognize that it might take extra to keep John =
Waldron (though unvested stock is a motivator for him to say), there are ot=
hers who could replace him, too.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Mayo=
 also suggested that Waldron could get paid <em>more</em> than Solomon=E2=
=80=94just as <strong>Tom Montag</strong>, a former top executive at Bank o=
f America who is now on the Goldman board, was paid more than <strong>Brian=
 Moynihan</strong>, the C.E.O. of Bank of America, a few years ago. He addi=
tionally worried, considering the =E2=80=9Coverall comp ratio=E2=80=9D was =
down for the firm, that giving Solomon and Waldron these $80 million awards
could be =E2=80=9Calienating=E2=80=9D for Goldman executives who did not re=
ceive similar incentives.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Mayo does acknowledge that =
Solomon and Waldron have done a =E2=80=9Cgood=E2=80=9D job of running Goldm=
an Sachs, but not, he says, a =E2=80=9Cperfect=E2=80=9D job. (In fairness, =
Goldman=E2=80=99s stock is up 172 percent in the past five years, more than=
 that of its two main rivals, JPMorgan Chase and Morgan Stanley.) He noted =
that Goldman has shown =E2=80=9Cgood=E2=80=9D growth
in revenue, earnings, and book value, and is =E2=80=9Cbetter positioned=E2=
=80=9D now in its two main business lines, investment banking and wealth an=
d asset management.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">He was less enamored of the=
 lackluster returns on equity, which the firm has been focused on improving=
=2E =E2=80=9CStrategically, they oversaw a=
 costly and failed effort in consum=
er banking and what we see as a failed GreenSky acquisition,=E2=80=9D Mayo =
wrote,
referring to Goldman=E2=80=99s purchase and subsequent offloading of its co=
nsumer lending operations=E2=80=94Marcus, the Apple Card, etcetera. =E2=80=
=9CThe Apple Card portfolio remains and, if sold, may involve a loss.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">By the way, Mayo has a price target on Goldma=
n=E2=80=99s stock of $680 per share, up about 5.3 percent from where it=E2=
=80=99s currently trading. I don=E2=80=99t think Mayo is necessarily agains=
t Solomon and Waldron
<em>getting</em> these awards, but is simply annoyed at the relatively low =
lift involved. Five years may seem like a long time in our crazy world, but=
 for executives to get this much compensation without having to achieve cer=
tain performance metrics along the way=E2=80=94a return-on-equity target, a=
 higher stock price, anything, really, that is more substantial than just s=
taying alive and not doing something egregious=E2=80=94well, that seems a b=
it crazy too. A fair point, although I=E2=80=99m skeptical that enough
Goldman shareholders will flock to Mayo=E2=80=99s cause at the annual meeti=
ng.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;">Goldman, for its part, said in a statement, =E2=80=9CThe firm has del=
ivered strong performance and the competition for our top talent has been e=
specially fierce, including from asset managers and other non-banks.=E2=80=
=9D And so the Goldman board of directors =E2=80=9Cwas determined to keep t=
his team in place=E2=80=94both to maintain our momentum and to have a very =
strong succession
plan.=E2=80=9D The =E2=80=9Cvalue of a restricted stock award,=E2=80=9D the=
 bank spokesperson added, =E2=80=9Cis tied directly to the performance of t=
he company.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
